76561198044516592,Recommended,233860,33696885,Posted: 21 July,all,Vivikus,"The game starts out as a confusing mess of frustration. We're so used to games that treat us like the fragile little emotional bags of crybaby, that when one comes along and expects us to be a true challenger, we don't know what to do.You start as a regular person.You must work hard to earn even enough to eat.You must obey the laws, or else.You must avoid bands of gang rapists that will put it in your butt, and then eat you.If you can manage to do that, and then run around a lot, you become a little faster at running. Suddenly you're a little more useful. One town has pleny of copper at a cheap price, and there is another far away that needs that copper and will pay 100c. more than the town your in sells it for. So you buy what you can carry, run, and trade it.You make a friend, they join you on your quest to merely stay alive.After many hours, you might have a small band of people. You're doing well. Staying within the laws, and making a small amount of money. Maybe you're mining metal and selling it. Maybe you're trading between the towns. Or maybe you're luring gangs close enough to towns that the town guards come out and beat them up, you then take all their clothes and weapons and sell them to the traders in town.After you grow some more, you start to fight small groups, or maybe you start to build your own town and recruit more to your cause.This game is for specific people that like DIFFICULT games. This game is for anyone who likes trading games with a spin of danger and total risk. This game is for those who don't cry about failure, but instead they look at what they could've done better.This game is for us.9/10would be 10/10 if I could que movement. I hate the AI pathing. Let me shift and click to que a series of movements to where I want to go, or to train my athletics/strength while I'm coordinating other tasks with other members of my group."
76561197996681211,Recommended,233860,35029795,Posted: 17 September,all,Ziggy Stardust,"Kenshi is a very nieche Game that surely is not for everyone. I recommend it to anyone who is a fan of classical Sandbox-MMORPG's - even though it is lacking multiplayer it has the deep crafting, the absolute freedom and quite a bit of character customization and developement. It very much is an RPG, it is less of an RTS as the pictures might suggest.Fans of Star Wars Galaxies, such as myself, may find themself reminded of that game when they step into the vast world this Game has to offer.I first read about this game when it was very early alpha and it was nothing but a squad management game with nothing much to it. Yet still the game managed to keep me interested by its very unique concept and style of genre.For an ""early access"" title by an indie dev team it is running fairly stable. It lacks some optimization but if you look into it a little you can fix most FPS issues yourself (by downloading texture optimization-mods or fiddling with the settings for a bit)It is highly encouraged to run it as experimental (by opting into the beta experiences) as you will miss out on regular hotfixes if you do not.All in all the graphics are nothing to be amazed by, even though I personally think it still manages to deliver beautiful scenes every now and then - a lot of graphics are notable placeholders aswell and will probably be enhanced later on.The Game has a lot of bugs, but nothing is really gamebreaking and In 40 Hours playtime I have yet to run into anything that really annoys me.Mods _really_ help customize your game experience. There is tons of potential in mod support, even though the possibilities are still limited - the devs plan to expand upon this (afaik)If you are looking for a challenging and interesting new World to explore and dive into in a type of game that you probably have not seen done yet, give Kenshi a try. Its definitely worth the 15€ it costs at the time of this review."
76561198035670678,Recommended,233860,22934757,"Posted: 12 May, 2016",all,ShrekIsMyDad,"If Mad Max, Samurai Champloo, and The Dark Tower had a weird kid that ran around shirtless with nothing but a rusty katana and an empty stomach, then it would be this game.The setting is unique, taking place in a varied post-apocalyptic enviroment that's soon to be expanded with a shiny new map. Combat is dangerous and every encounter has the potential to be your last. Numerous factions have their wars and alliances, and you can participate if you want, or just loot the corpses like a gross human vulture that has no honor.The problem with the games are thus: The engine isn't the best in the world, so graphically it's rather unimpressive, however the artists have done a great job with worldbuilding and locations look unique enough that graphical limitations don't hinder the game at all. Another possible gripe is that the early game's combat is very, very hard. You will be knocked out for most of your time with Kenshi without proper preperation. It's stupid to brave the wasteland alone, you aren't the Dragonborn; you're Jeff from accounting who's decided to become a vagrant warrior with little to know chance of survival. That being said, a larger party and training vis a vie the practice dummies can make combat easier.All in all Kenshi has been developed slowly over a long period of time, and it's clear the developers have put love into their game. Updates are progressing steadily and adding in new content and features. Kenshi's a good game now, but it'll be a great game when it gets released."
76561198027117855,Recommended,233860,25961220,"Posted: 9 October, 2016",all,Clint Eastwood,"9/10! I love this game! I am not usually one that enjoys really difficult games, but there is something about the brutal difficulty of this game that actually keeps me around. It's not like ""Oh I'm not good enough..."" kinda hard, it's more ""I need patience and dedication to prevail"" kinda hard. Basically, you start as a nobody. There are different backgrounds and starts, which I love, but I also love that the game is unforgiving. You can't just kill a group of raiders, hell, you probably can't even kill one at the start. The difficulty of this game is appropriate, and lends to the brutality of the harsh reality in which your characters live. With time, one can really succeed and have fun with this game. The challenges along the way, those are really the best part. I am a self-professed save-scummer when it comes to many games, but despite saving very often, I find myself reverting to old loads less often in this game than others. Devastating things occur to my party, but the way it happens... most of the time I just roll with it!This game features multiple ways to play, perhaps one of it's coolest features. You can get by as a lone wolf, stealing and killing while living on the run. Perhaps you yourself wish to organize a group to raid cities and farms. Maybe you wish to raise an army to do with what you please as you traverse the wastelands... in any case, you have a great deal of freedom. Basically, you can play it like a single player RPG, or more like an RTS, city builder, merchant goods management, etc. There are a few bugs, but nothing really gamebreaking. Another feature I love is that they allow you to import your old characters/buildings and so on into new versions of the game as it approaches release. There are factions in the game, and it is particularly interesting when you get involved with any of them. The factions are all unique and have interesting relationships with one another. Luring that band of bandits up to that Holy Nations City you visited may be the perfect distraction you need to rob them blind.As I mentioned before, this game is BRUTAL! My beloved characters have been enslaved, tortured/forcefully starved to death, murdered in cold blood and even eaten alive... that's right, I said EATEN ALIVE!!! Normally in games when my characters get, let's say, eaten alive, I save-scum to the save before that happened. This game encourages me to go along with the brutality though. I had a party of 17 characters or so, while running to a certain city, we were attacked. We fended off the Fog Men at first... but they kept coming... hoardes of them! All but two of my characters were left standing, carrying the wounded bodies of two other characters to safety (which in itself had my blood rushing!). As 4 of my characters got to safety, rested up and healed up, 3 were EATEN ALIVE by the Fog Men. I used what little money I had and sold everything to hire 2 more characters to join the party. We went out and managed to pick off the Fog Men that escorted our friends by setting up ambushes at tactical points. Thus far I have saved all but 1 of the captured members of my party (minus the 3 that were EATEN ALIVE), doing tactical stealth missions, solo runs and distraction assaults.Overall this game is outstanding! The aesthetic feel of it is perfect, mixing the feel of like a sumurai feudal system in the post-apocalypse. The difficulty of the game can make it a tough pill to initially swallow, but it is well worth it. The characters and races are unique (I love the Hive characters and the robotic mechanid ones, sooo cool!) Everything is fitting for the environment, nothing stands out as too high tech or too low tech. You can tell that this is the remnance of a world that once had tech, but that technology is long forgotten. There is electricity to some extent, but only what windmills and such can generate. Think Mad Max and/or Waterworld tech. Despite the brutal difficulty and the patience/sacrifice needed to succeed, I would give this game a 9/10 (as of patch 0.93 or so). I anticipate my score my go up when the game reaches full release."
