,Recommended,233860,21957530,"Posted: 20 March, 2016",all,OPG Godsend,"Firstly, my 'hours played' isn't accurate, I've played more than it shows. I had a weird stint where Steam Overlay didn't work for a couple weeks and blah blah.Anyway, this game is great.It's one major feature, one that people either love or hate, is that it's a true sandbox. At this point, there is no objective, no beginning - middle - or end.You choose a specific start (the starts that you choose from are kind of a template of the type of role play you're looking for) then.... well, whatever you want.Want to go over there? Do it. Want to start a base up and make it into a city sim? Have at it. Want to slaughter everyone in a town? Knock yourself out. There's a lot of stuff to do, but some people can't find enjoyment in doing it if they don't have something the game is telling them to work forward to - which isn't a bad thing, people can like whatever they want.There's a lot to be had in this game;- Party Based RPG- Squad Management (multiple squads)- Buy/Sell Merchant sim- City Builder & Management- Pickup and play for fifteen minutes or hours- It's... Just a giant sandbox, you can do damn-near anything.Something that I wont add to the list of it's features is its modibility, it's ridiculously easy - but there's only like, ten mods made for it, which is for the best anyways since the next planned update to the game is an entirely new map.If you like games that blend fifty different genre's together and don't mind there not being a point, you'll most likely enjoy this game as much as I have.There's a wierd 'either love it or hate it' review battle with this game, people claiming that if you say something bad about the game then you're an idiot and if you say somehting good about it you're a ravenous fanboy - the old ""Everyone's opinion matter as long as it is in full support of mine"" rhetoric seen in all games/movies.Honestly, it's a great game that has come a long, loooong way, and it gets exponentionally more fun with each update.TL:DR -- A ton of genre's slapped together very well.- Almost out of Alpha; soon to be fully featured.- Has no end goal - you make you're own up (in true roleplay fashion)- Can be played as little or as often as you want, there's currently (may not ever be) actual missions, so there's no ""Let me just finish this part""- I like it, you might like it, try the demo (yeah, it has a demo, for some reason video game companies refuse to make demos anymore) it's available on the Lo-Fi website (steam too?)"
76561197975218065,Recommended,233860,24435879,"Posted: 20 July, 2016",all,Defektiv,"This is roughly how it went for me. The first 10 hours I was just running away from things and reloading, cursing at the game and wondering how you were supposed to play this if you just got jumped all the time. The next 10 hours was spent discovering things, some on my own and some from searching. I got a small group of people together and saved up several thousand working resource nodes outside the cities. Whenever I had to travel though I was just running away from things and reloading, cursing at the game and wondering how you were supposed to play this if you just got jumped all the time.Then I started to get my bearings in the game. I learned that losing is part of the experience, literally part of the experience. If you pick an even fight and don't come out on top, you've still gained big defensive stats on anyone that didn't die. At that point, about 30 hours deep into the experience, I realized I just started. Game mechanics start springing up and spider-webbing outward. Character advancement, technology research, crafting, settlement management, supply runs, training, assaults, battles, wars. Now every time I assemble my elite crew of four to the gate, I get excited that I have so many options to choose from. We go to a city, make some money, recruit more people for the town, work their strength up a little to make some more money nearby, buy some supplies and sneak them back up.The game creeps up on you and owns you with complex, interesting things to do. The mechanics, dialog, options and behavior of npcs are deep and seem very well thought out. I often find myself doing something I fully expect to result in losing something and figure out the game already thought of it and provided an option. And if you're worried there may not be enough RPG in it for you, each and every character you recruit is playable, equippable and trainable independently. The vanilla cap is I think 30 right now total recruitable, but there is a mod already that increases it to 256. Give it some time and you'll be hooked."
76561197975245018,Recommended,233860,33030441,Posted: 30 June,all,Llaerrick,"This game has a steep learning curve.The first 30 minutes was more or less figuring things out and getting use to the UI (and some times bizarre camera angles).The game is not immediately intuitive and a bit more guidance at the start would have been appreciated. There are some tutorial tips and hints but still a little bit more help would be good for starters. That said, once you figure out the general controls/gameplay, the game starts to shine.Gameplay itself is pretty much exactly what is advertised. Squad-based sandbox RPG where you can pretty much do everything (within limits). It's pretty much about surviving and gathering enough currency to employ more characters (which you can customize within limits) and building up a decent team/squad/company. Thereafter it's mostly point-and-click (or right click) to achieve objectives within the game play. Battles are RTS-like based on character modifiers and equipment. Realistically, most battles are about numbers, gear and attributes.Right off the bat, your characters are generally weak and need to be trained/levelled up (xp and ranks are gained by doing specific things, eg. running around unencumbered trains athletics, runing around encumbered trains strength, and generally doing certain things improve certain traits. It is possible to hire better characters but these are expensive for a beginner character (although getting currency is not too difficult).The AI isn't very good right now. The easiest way to earn currency is to lure enemies to a friendly settlement and have their guards take them out. You then loot the unconscious/dead enemies, sell their stuff, and rinse and repeat. The squad-AI is also a little limited right now with limited tactical oversight and commands. It would be nice if they added a little more depth into the tactical command system (eg. grouping, assist target, formations, etc). Hotkeys for battle commands (such as to go passive or block) would be useful and should be developed.There is trading (limited right now to mainly selling loot and produce, rather than selling low buying high) and crafting. The mechanic is there but needs work.As with most open sandbox-types, you can go about however you want: - build a small farm-sted, roam as bandits/mercenaries, build a fortress/bastion, trade etc. There are multiple and myriad factions in game but diplomacy right now is pretty basic (kill or commit crime against faction = worsening relations and bounty). As the game progresses, I hope more is done to improve the faction/diplomacy mechanics.Generally, the game itself runs quite well on my robust but dated rig. Although, it gets laggy after about 2 hours or so of play but nothing a simple reboot wouldn't solve.All in all, for an early access it's pretty fun so far. Looking forward to more development and progress."
