76561198067483715,Recommended,233860,30762760,Posted: 26 March,all,Randy Savage,"Before I begin, I won't sit around and pretend like Kenshi is a perfect game. You are looking at an Early Access title. Maps will get wiped. A town you spent hours building in that perfect spot between two mountains will be gone when the next chunk of the map releases. The game is constantly being changed, and will continue to be in that state for a long time. The graphics are somewhat dated, an artifact of when the game first came out. Collisions can be very buggy, and you will probably have to deal with picking up your squadmate that won't stop blocking the stairs. The autopathing will do what you want it to do half the time if the distance is further than 50 meters. At least once, the captured dude that you put down will rocket into the sky and fall like a meteor because you approached him from the wrong side. That being said, I'll go into what Kenshi is, and why I recommend it:As the description will tell you, Kenshi is an open world, squad-based RPG that takes place in a post-apocalypse style region (I say ""style"" because of some disputes about this canonically). ""Open world"" needs to be emphasized hugely. There is no overarching task to the game other than survival. Any goals you have in Kenshi are self-set. However, certain items can incentivize you to explore the world; a map from an old library that shows you the far-away location of an ancient armory, or a bounty for a bandit king, or a rumor from a crazy, inebriated man that turns out to be nothing. The absence of any concrete goal isn't new to the sandbox-survival genre, but it's fairly unique in Kenshi, where there isn't any multiplayer. I initially thought this would result in the telltale problem surrounding nearly all games in this genre, but I learned later that two main elements of the game ensure you don't exhaust it:1. The map of Kenshi is absolutely massive. Only half of it is available at the moment (as the developers are constantly working on new sections), but in my experience, going from the south end of the continent to the north took an actual, real hour without utilizing the speed features (Sims-style buttons that accelerate time). In my 31 or so hours of the game, between two squads, I have only explored a good quarter of the available half-map. The land is varied and unique as well. Swamps filled with wandering assassins and blood spiders, a crater brimming with robot spiders and horrible giraffe-like monsters that run as fast as a car, or river valleys dotted with small farms belonging to a theocratic empire. The developers have clearly spent their time cultivating each biome/area to make it feel alive, complete with ruins of an old space war, alien-like flora and fauna, and a soundtrack that mixes pad-based wasteland ambient noise with a strange asian tone to create an otherworldly tone.2. Kenshi is a difficult, unforgiving game. I am aware most people see that warning and roll their eyes, as every undercooked developement team tries to desperately convince the consumer-base that their game is ""the next Dark Souls"", a marketing tactic that needs doing away with. But Kenshi is truly the embodiment of unforgiving. If I can give one piece of credit to the trailer, it is for having the phrase ""the world doesn't care about you"". Nearly everything in Kenshi will try to kill you. I distinctly remember within my first five minutes of the game, my efforts to attack a group of hungry bandits resulted in my character being beaten nearly to death and stripped of his shoddy weapon. Everything in Kenshi starts out stronger than you. Becoming stronger in this game is a matter of how much you are willing to risk. You will not become better with a weapon by targeting weaker enemies. You constantly have to aim above where you are, and that risk can result in being imprisoned by slavers, or captured by guards, or kidnapped and eaten alive by fog-men. Even if you fail (assuming you live), some good comes from the encounter; you gain toughness, and will be harder to fall in the coming fights, as long as you tend to your wounds. This mechanic is the central point of Kenshi; you will not become better unless you fight someone better than you. So you need to find or buy some friends, train them up with you, and make a name for yourself.---------But what I find to be the most unique part of Kenshi is how you can become attached to these characters, despite them not being attributed with a real personality (save a fair amount of unqiue hires). I would save a slave passed out from bloodloss, nurse him back to health, and equip him with clothes, hoping he would join my party. And when he was kidnapped by northern cannibals and locked in a ruin with 50+ men well above my strength, I would try and devise a plan with my other party members to get him out despite it being much easier and efficient to leave him to die. Nothing would be gained by saving him, but we still did it because he was part of our squad.That is where Kenshi shines, at least for me. It makes you care about these people that have never uttered anything more than trade dialogue. It makes you chase after that old man that was really awful at learning how to swing the fragment axe that was too big for him, after he was imprisoned in a tower of the Holy Nation. It makes you keep that dumb-looking basket on that short dude's head because you're certain he has to wear it because you decided he was the assassin when you first rescued him. It makes you give every shiny new nodachi to that girl with the best armor, because she was your first recuit and you just know she has to get the good loot.Kenshi doesn't pull its punches. It is dedicated to making you fail and wiping your squad. Your death will likely not be ceremonious: you're probably going to die to skin-spiders more than you are to an evil slaver army you tried to attack. When you get imprisoned and your Katana worth 100,000 Cats is stripped from you, I hope you're ready to spend 30 actual minutes checking each container in each guardhouse for it. If you really really want that Falling Sun manufactured by the Catun Scrapmasters, you better be ready to spend a whole in-game night picking that 0.6% chance to succeed lock with the shop guard sleeping nearby. If you've finally decided you're sick of your friends bleeding out and you want to get some Skeletons (robots) on your side, you better start shelling out thousands of Cats for repair kids, or else they're going down quick. You will think you're invincible after finally finding an Edgewalker Naginata, and you will probably get your♥♥♥♥♥handed to you by some bum with a rusty chopper that's done nothing but fight his whole life.You are never too high on the food chain to be invincible. Believe me, I know:I had raided all of the northern armories and found two Edgewalker weapons. I had a squad of 6 people: Dave, Kai, Soto, Hobbes, Kara, and Gynn. Through almost 20 hours of training, they had become true warriors. We had accumulated 120,000 Cats from our exploits, and were ready to finally settle down and establish a town for some money before we explored the next part of the map. Since the swamp was perfect for farming, we saw a little flat plane near the southeast on the map and decided to make our home there. We were off with nearly 30 building materials, a month's worth of food cubes, and some advanced health kits. When we finally got to the area, we noticed there were a fair amount of ruins, usually a sign of danger. And even despite this warning, we pressed on.And when we reached the plane, our long days of training, weapons worth their weight in gold, and samurai armor stolen from shops around the continent meant nothing. Against the blood spiders, swamp raptors, and acid rain, we were fallen within seconds and our unconscious bodies were eaten by the monsters. Weeks of training, great escapes, fireside meals, stealthy heists, and grueling battles - they were all undone in seconds.That is Kenshi."
76561198157202252,Recommended,233860,29012901,Posted: 4 January,all,PusPaw,"Addicted. While still a work in progress with an admittedly long development cycle, Kenshi offers dynamic factional interaction, a functioning economy, and a SPRAWLING world married to interesting lore. The sheer scope and freedom of self-driven narrative offer deep replayability, while the XP grind and research tree keep number junkies engaged.The depth can seem daunting as, right out of the gate, you're hit with a chargen system awash in variables. Stick with it. The core systems, be they crafting, research, farming, theft, or combat will shed their mystery in short order, leaving you free to create the game you wish, not the one a developer has decided you will undertake.Early on, embrace your failings. You'll die. You'll lose. You'll assail the heavens with ""WTF?"", but it's the best way for the realities of Kenshi's world to sink in. It's no JRPG and it can feel nearly cruel. That's just the fun you're feeling.Pros:+ nearly infinite replayability.+ engaging world-building with interesting and consistent lore+ the capacity to build BIG groups of henchmen / men at arms+ satisfying tech research / crafting / building+ the world is HUGE+ (in case you missed it) - the world is HUGE+ free-form gameplayCons:- early access (doesn't bother me, but some loathe EA titles)- infrequent world-breaks resulting from patches- graphical hiccups / oft-times bland imagery- upper tier hardware required for truly smooth play- a myriad of beta-level bugs and niggling issuesIt's hard to convey Kenshi's ability to capture the imagination. I haven't been this enamored of a title since the dawn of Space Engineers. Kudos and high fives all around both to the man responsible for this project from its birth, and the team he has recently surrounded himself with to complete it. Props."
