,Recommended,233860,632744,"Posted: 30 August, 2013",all,The Burning of Prospero.,"-Early Access Review-The game of an alternative universe which is a strange mixture between apocolypse/Japan/RPG, the game where you cannot be a one man army and you actually have to work to be something useful. The game has a number of starting points for you to choose from with varied difficulty. To be honest when I first bought the game I was a little let down, the content was awkwardly done, the terrain was dull and lifeless, the pathfinding was just... horrific, base building was more than a chore and the optimisation was less than good.Here we are now! The game has come on leaps and bounds and the developers seem to truly listen to you. We now have sound, good basebuilding mechanics, Squads that seem worthwhile (You actually feel a little heart broken if they die), pathfinding has improved although its still not quiet there and a number of new features and terrain additions have been added.Pros:- Interesting setting- ALOT to do once you get the hang of it- Buildings, lots of buildings.- Combat is actually quite fun, nothing better than watching 40 people scrap it out over your little farm.- I like the ""Everyman"" (Everywoman) type of setup- Getting chased for MILES by angry Sand Ninjas and Bandits.Cons:- Pathfinding and wall placement is still hit 'n' miss at times- Getting new squad members can have you running for hours at a time, would love some periodic respawning- AI can be dumb, I had squad members watching my team die while they mined stone- Alot of stuff still cannot be sold which makes early game money making a case of stealing items of corpses (Vulture simulator)- The real lack of need for water, food or anything really.Overall a nice game, plenty of game play options and very sandboxy, even more so with future updates. If you have some spare cash and time, why not build a nice functional little down and shank some cannibals?Current rating: 6.5/10~Liquifiction"
