76561198025045609,Recommended,233860,33906754,Posted: 30 July,all,Linksworth,"It's not a game with a plot, per se, but just trying to survive and explore the world can give rise to some amazing narratives:In my first few hours of play, I befriended a disgraced warrior, and got captured by slavers who then left us for dead in the desert. After heading to the nearest town to buy a hacksaw to cut off our shackes, we were chased out by xenophobes, and picked a fight with a small family of goats that nearly killed us.It's been two in-game months now, and I've got a squad of 12 people who've constructed a fully-fledged base... which is currently under siege by ravenous cannibals.If managing a small band of warriors/theives/farmers/traders just trying to survive in a harsh world sounds like your cup of tea, definitely give Kenshi a try."
,Recommended,233860,33862974,Posted: 28 July,all,Teflonto,"I originally bought this a few months back and refunded it after about 50 minutes. It looked like an early 2000's RPG, it was clunky, it was buggy and it ran like a legless Dog on my old graphics card.I upgraded my card last month and for some reason, something about the idea behind this game kept it on my wishlist. I picked it up again today, and I just put 6.5 hours into it effortlessly. It still looks like an early 2000's RPG, it still feels clunky, it's still a little buggy and it now runs like a dog with 3 legs... But something clicked.I started with my band of 5 misfits - a facimile of myself, my friend, a robot, a lizard man and a terrifying looking woman and I was dumped into a wasteland. I decided to look up bits and pieces from Wikis as I played and had questions, and this approach has worked in the main. I explored the first town, which mostly seemed to be ruins, got wrecked about 4 times just trying to explore, and then came across a big city.It was here that things started to turn around. Robot and Lizardman were set up for permanent mining duty. The other three travelled out to look for a trading city. On finding one, they started to bring back their stuff to the starting city. It was here that I bought a building and set up a base. That base then also became a shop, and a research station, and a jack-of-all-bases as I started to set each character up in their role. I was the builder. My friend was the caravan. My crazy-eyed woman was the researcher. The lizard and the robot were miners.This should have felt repetetive - backwards and forwards, slowly crawling forward toward my goal... But it's all been incredibly engrossing so far. Emergent events happening here and there, New options opening up from research... I'm just incredibly glad that I second guessed this game and bought it back again."
