76561198063701370,Recommended,233860,34475316,Posted: 25 August,all,B1ack A1ch3myst,"So I've owned this game for a while now and I can still remember when I first got it on a whim. I thought ""Okay, another game in beta that seems a shred above the rest. Cool, I'll give it five minutes to impress me."" Almost ten minutes in, I was about to write it off and move on but I was feeling generous and pushed through it, something kept me playing. This was back when there was no tutorial, so learning the UI was very frustrating yet it felt kinda rewarding, even though I had literally no idea what to do.Then I kept playing, and learning, and I felt like I was actually figuring out a world with various cultures, regions and peoples. You learn things early on like ""Hey, don't ♥♥♥♥ with Beak Things alone"" and ""Okranites are REALLY racist,"" and other things about the world that gives you a sense of satisfaction in just knowing thigns that help you survive in the map's different regions.Now that there have been numerous updates, the game is super polished, in my opinion. I personally love the skill and combat system, the building and crafting mechanics, and the little hidden gems of story in the wastelands. That brings me to another point. Story. If you're looking for a driven campaign, there isn't one. You make your own, which in a lot of games seems a lazy development choice. But in Kenshi, it allowed me to feel super invested in my character(s) endeavors. I have this whole little head-cannon for every single character and it ties into how I met them, what they do in the community, and other little things I just make up (I should really make it into a story on the reddit page or something one day). I use the products that my people make to fund expeditions into the really sketchy parts of the world to find treasure, sending the stealthiest members of my faction to free slaves wherever I find them.If you're thinking about buying the game, do it. The devs have been at this game for a long time and seem super invested. Every update they put out is meaningful and almost always adds a lot of stuff to do or see. It'll be rough at first, but hey, it's to be expected when you're dropped into a harsh, unforgiving world that you know nothing about and trying to survive and thrive. This game doesn't hold your hand and is arguably more fun because of it. I keep coming back for more even after over 200 hours of gameplay."
