,Recommended,233860,8893794,"Posted: 28 January, 2014",all,Rye Bread,"A lot of people worry about buying Early Access games. And they should. Early Access is a risky investment for the consumer. But you don't need to worry about this developer. This is a solid team making a great game. I've had it several years now. It started off rough around the edges, buggy, unstable, but fun. I had a lot of fun in its early stages. Its a testament to the core aspects of the game that I loved it even with its Pre-Alpha quirks. It pre dates Early Access on Steam altogether. After all this time. The original lone developer, Chris, (and now a complete team) made something really special. Its got a ways to go. But it has grown exponentially since when I bought it even.I bought it just after they added sound to the game. I want to say that was 2012 but I don't quite remember. I had my eye on it prior to that but that is when I took the plunge. I started off confused. I wasn't really sure how the game worked. The style was nice but the world was a little off in the ways that any game is prior to an alpha release. Despite that, I had a great time. Its fun just roaming a desert. Its fun talking to the weird inhabitants.  It was awesome when I finally WON a fight. And base building is as fun as it is time consuming.I was running from city to city, gathering resources, gaining a comrade or two in the process. Booking it past Bandits and Ninjas to the safety of city. And, once I was strong enough, fighting back, with mixed results. It is interesting that the sense of relief I feel when my limping character carries a bleeding out comrade to the safety of city walls... is immediately followed by the desire to venture outside of those walls yet again. Thats Kenshi for you. Its all in the goals you set for yourself.The original map was a massive desert. Fun but monotonous. The new map adds quite a bit of spice to that. Swamps. Fog Islands, Coastal areas, Forests, Mountains, and a new and improved desert. More is to come. Only half of the map is available at the moment, but it is huge. I'm not even close to discovering all the major cities and I have put 20 hours this week on exploring it (and that is all I have been doing with my squad)First the danger outside of those walls was Ninjas and Bandits. New updates added Cannibals, wildlife... fog men. There are hostile areas (particularly in the North) you should back off from unless you have a group of solid fighters. Either the enemy's numbers or skill will overwhelm a new player there. I really enjoy the creature design. Familiar creatures exist like dogs, bulls, turtles and then there are Garrus, Beak Things, and some creatures that should be avoided altogether because they are four stories tall.Its a journey for your squad and its a personal thing, because the game doesn't tell you where to go. It doesn't tell you to stop until all of your guys are dead. It just says, ""GO."" From a guy with a sword to an impressive company of nomadic traders. From a crippled old man stranded in the desert to builder of a city. An escaped slave to the conqueror of an empire."
