76561198025829832,Recommended,233860,13799816,"Posted: 2 January, 2015",all,Docturnal,"I got this game very close to its coming out on Steam Greenlight.  It has changed a lot since then, and it is awesome to see the developer's vision grow into a playable reality.   This is what a badass game looks like... without the AAA stiffs saying ""No make this game, no make that game, no make another CoD since that is what makes money.""This game is brutal, in the most rewarding way possible.  I have to admit that early on I let development get a bit further before investing a lot of time in it; dying on the character creation screen due to a pack of roving bandits was a bit of a shock.   Kenshi brought me that first--the first time I'd ever died (in game) while making a character for any game, ever.  That issue is long gone, but few games bring that visceral sense of loss of your personal pixellated avatar(s) home as well as Kenshi.Which brings me to my next point, permadeath is so awesome when you know that you can build your base up, research, trade, pirate, murder, craft, or somehow launch yourself from a measly peasant unskilled in battle, to a slightly stronger peasant that is marginally better in battle.  Never do you feel like you're king of the world, untouchable by the masses, and the NPC bandits are far too willing to remind you that your ♥♥♥♥e in fact does stink, as they disembowel you and walk away as if nothing happened.This game is the type that grows on you, and gets inside your head.  It's a very slow paced game, but offers (even in its unfinished state) an amazing strategic role-playing game that lets you build a shack, build a town, build a city, make rum, and grow hemp.  All that with squad-based combat.  Hurry up and finish already!For those of you on the fence, if an old-school game catches your fancy, don't miss out on this game.  Pure Sandbox/Strategy/City-building/Crafting/Murdering/RPG goodness!"
